<setup>
  <function name="approx0" variable="t" domain="[0,2]">$approx0Exp</function>
  <function name="approx1" variable="t" domain="[2,4]">$approx1Exp</function>
  <function name="approx2" variable="t" domain="[4,6]">$approx2Exp</function>
  <function name="k">$kEntered</function>
</setup>

  <p>
    Consider the initial value problem
    <me>
      \frac{dy}{dt} = \frac12 (y + 1), \ y(0) = 0
    </me>
  </p>

  <p>
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the initial value to find the point on the solution <m>y(t)</m>
          where <m>t=0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Point <m>=\left(0,y(0)\right)=</m><answer name="point">(0,0)</answer>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the differential equation to find the slope of the line tangent to the solution <m>y(t)</m> where <m>t=0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Slope <m>=\displaystyle\frac{dy}{dt}=</m><answer name="slope">1/2</answer>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the point <mathInput disabled>$point</mathInput> and
          slope <mathInput disabled>$slope</mathInput> that you've found to find the equation
          of the line tangent to the solution at <m>t=0</m>.  Be sure to write the tangent line equation as a function of <m>t</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>y=</m><answer name="approx0Exp">t/2</answer>

        </p>
        <graph size="small" xmin="-2" ymin="-2" xmax="8" ymax="8" fixAxes="true" showNavigation="false" grid="true">
          $approx0
        </graph>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Notice that in the figure above we see a plot of the approximating tangent line you found in (b),
          <mathInput disabled>y= $approx0Exp</mathInput>, on the domain
          <m>[0,2]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Now we are going to use the point <m>(2,y(2))</m> from the tangent line above along with the differential
          equation <m>\frac{dy}{dt}=\frac{1}{2}(y+1)</m> to find the equation
          of a corresponding tangent line on the domain <m>[2,4]</m>. Again, be sure to write the tangent line equation as a function of <m>t</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Point <m>=(2,y(2))=</m><answer>(2,1)</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          Slope <m>=</m><answer>1</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          Tangent line equation: <m>y=</m><answer name="approx1Exp">t-1</answer>
        <graph size="small" xmin="-2" ymin="-2" xmax="8" ymax="8"  fixAxes="true" showNavigation="false" grid="true">
          $approx0
          $approx1
        </graph>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Repeat this process to find another approximating tangent line
          for the domain <m>[4,6]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Point <m>=</m><answer>(4,3)</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          Slope <m>=</m><answer>2</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>y=</m><answer name="approx2Exp">2t-5</answer>

        <graph size="small" xmin="-2" ymin="-2" xmax="8" ymax="8" fixAxes="true" showNavigation="false" grid="true">
          $approx0
          $approx1
          $approx2
        </graph>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          It turns out that the given initial value problem, 
          <me>
            \frac{dy}{dt} = \frac12 (y + 1), \ y(0) = 0,
          </me> 
          has a solution
          of the form <m>y=ke^{t/2} - 1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If the initial value is <m>y(0)=0</m>, what must be the value of
          <m>k</m>?
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>k=</m><mathInput name="kEntered"/><answer name="kExp"><award><when>$kExp=1</when></award></answer>
        </p>

      </li>

      <!--
      <li>
        <setup>
          <conditionalContent name="nextStep" condition="$kExp.creditAchieved = 1"> 
            <math name="correctkEntered" extend="$kEntered.value"/>
            <math name="IVPsoln" simplify>$correctkEntered.value*e^(t/2) - 1</math>
          </conditionalContent>
        </setup>      
        <p>
          Then verify that
          <m>y=</m><mathInput disabled><math simplify>$k e^(t/2) - 1</math></mathInput>
          is in fact a solution by substituting it into both sides of the
          differential equation.
        </p>
        <p><m>\frac{dy}{dt}=</m><answer>1/2 e^(t/2)</answer></p>
        <p><m>\frac{1}{2}(y+1)=</m><answer>1/2 e^(t/2)</answer></p>
      </li>
      -->

      <li>
        <p>
          Finally, by completing the sentences that follow the figure, discuss how the graph of the three approximating line segments compares with the graph of the solution.
        </p>
        <graph xmin="-2" ymin="-2" xmax="8" ymax="8" fixAxes="true" showNavigation="false" grid="true">
          $approx0
          $approx1
          $approx2
          <function styleNumber="2" variable="t" domain="[0,6]" name="SolnFxn">$k e^(t/2) - 1</function>
          <label anchor="(2.5,5.75)"><m><math simplify>y=$k e^(t/2) - 1</math></m></label>
        </graph>
        <p>
          We see at the initial point, <m>(0,0)</m>, the tangent line <choiceInput inline name="a1">
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>shares the same <m>y</m>-value as</choice>
            <choice>has a larger <m>y</m>-value than</choice>
            <choice>has a smaller <m>y</m>-value than</choice>
          </choiceInput> the solution curve <m><math simplify>y = $SolnFxn</math></m>, and as we let <m>t</m> increase in value, the first tangent line aproximation's <m>y</m>-values <choiceInput inline name="a2">
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>overestimate</choice>
            <choice>underestimate</choice>
            <choice>exactly match</choice>
          </choiceInput> the <m>y</m>-values of the solution curve.  This leads to the second and third tangent line approximations also <choiceInput inline name="a3">
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>overestimating</choice>
            <choice>underestimating</choice>
            <choice>exactly matching</choice>
          </choiceInput> the true values of the solution curve and doing so with increasing error as <m>t</m> increases.
        </p>
        <p>
          <answer><award><when>$a1.selectedIndices=2 and $a2.selectedIndices=3 and $a3.selectedIndices=3</when></award></answer>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>